{
  "text": "To examine the field-dependence of 1 H-C 2 arising from Mn 2+ , we measured 1 H N -C 2 rates for the [CITATION_1] C/ 15 N-labeled SRY/DNA-EDTA-Mn 2+ complex at 1 H-frequencies of 500, 600, and 800 MHz. Fig. 5 shows the correlations between the C 2 rates measured at the different fields. Linear regressions indicate that the 1 H-C 2 rates at 600 and 800 MHz are higher than the corresponding rates at 500 MHz by factors of 1.02 and 1.08, respectively. (Note that these numbers are not precise because of experimental errors.) The field dependence of 1 H-C 2 arising from Mn 2+ is very weak in this magnetic field range (11.7-18.8 T). This finding leads one to two conclusions. First, the contribution from Curie-spin relaxation is indeed negligible, which is consistent with the considerations described above. Second, the PRE correlation time s c is almost field-independent. Considering that the experimentally determined s c is smaller than the rotational correlation time s r , this suggests a very weak field-dependence for the electron relaxation time s s of Mn 2+ at high magnetic field (>10 T) in contrast to the strong field dependence observed at low (<3 T) magnetic field [CITATION_2] .",
